if selected == " What is Stocks?":
        st.markdown("<h2 class='Heading' >What is Stocks?</h2>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        st.markdown("<div class='ans'><div class='imgContainer'><img src='https://www.fisdom.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/800x600-09.jpg' class='img' ><img src='https://i.ibb.co/7r3Rvqz/Screenshot-2024-04-04-235316.png' class='img' > </div><p class='Para'>A <b><i>stock</i></b> is essentially a piece of ownership in a company. When a company decides to go public, it divides its ownership into units called shares. These shares are then sold to investors on a marketplace called a stock exchange.</br></br>Think of a <b><i>stock exchange</i></b> like a giant marketplace where buyers and sellers come together to trade stocks. The exchange sets the rules and regulations for trading, and ensures that all transactions are conducted fairly and efficiently.</br></br><b><i>Here's an analogy:</i></b> imagine a company as a pizza. When the company goes public, it's like cutting the pizza into slices (shares). These slices are then sold to people (investors) on a platform (stock exchange).</p></div>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        

if selected == "How Stock Price Moves?":
        st.markdown("<h2 class='Heading' >How Stock Price Moves?</h2>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        st.markdown("<div class='ans'><div class='imgContainer'><img src='https://i.ibb.co/vHbQKJP/SnD.jpg' class='img' > </div><p class='Para'> Stock prices fluctuate throughout the day due to a tug-of-war between supply and demand. Here's a breakdown of the key factors:</br></br> <b><i>Supply:</i></b> This refers to the amount of a particular good or service that producers are willing to sell at different price points. Generally, as the price increases, suppliers are incentivized to produce and sell more.</li> </br></br><b><i>Demand:</i></b> This represents the amount of a good or service that consumers are willing to buy at different price points.Generally, as the price increases, suppliers are incentivized to produce and sell more.</br></br><b><i>High Demand, Low Supply = Price Increase:</i></b> If many investors want to buy a stock (high demand) but there are few shares available (low supply), the price will tend to rise.</br></br><i><b>Low Demand, High Supply = Price Decrease:</i></b> Conversely, if more investors want to sell a stock (low demand) than buy it (high supply), the price will likely fall.</p></div>", unsafe_allow_html=True)

if selected == "Fundamental Analysis":
        st.markdown("<h2 class='Heading' >Fundamental Analysis</h2>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        st.markdown("<div class='ans'><div class='imgContainer'><img src='https://i.ibb.co/R6gSfXy/mdf.jpg' class='img'><img src='https://i.ibb.co/5xSdFbS/Fundamental-Analysis-upscayl-16x-ultramix-balanced.png' class='img' ><img src='https://i.ibb.co/7QZcwFW/Who-Uses-Fundamental-Analysis-upscayl-4x-realesrgan-x4plus.png' class='img' > </div><p class='Para'>Fundamental analysis is an investment approach that dives into the underlying value of a company or asset to determine if it's a good investment. It's like looking at a company's financial health and prospects to assess its true worth, rather than just focusing on the current stock price.</br></br><b><i> Company Financials:</i></b> This is a deep dive into a company's financial statements, including income statements, balance sheets, and cash flow statements. Analysts examine metrics like revenue, earnings, profit margins, debt levels, and return on equity to understand the company's financial performance, profitability, and efficiency. </br></br><b><i>Industry Analysis:</i></b> Fundamental analysis doesn't happen in a vacuum. Analysts also consider the overall health and trends of the industry the company operates in. This includes factors like competition, regulations, and technological advancements that might impact the company's future. </br></br><b><i>Management Assessment:</i></b> The quality and experience of a company's management team are crucial factors. Analysts evaluate the management's track record, decision-making skills, and strategic vision to gauge their ability to steer the company towards success. </br></br><b><i>Economic Conditions:</i></b> Broad economic factors like interest rates, inflation, and economic growth can significantly impact a company's performance. Understanding the economic climate helps analysts assess potential risks and opportunities for the company. </br></br><b><i>Valuation Techniques:</i></b> Based on the analysis of the above factors, investors can use valuation techniques to estimate a company's intrinsic value. This essentially means determining what the company is actually worth based on its fundamentals, rather than just its current market price. </br></br><b><i>The Goal:</i></b> By performing fundamental analysis, investors aim to identify: </br></br><b><i> Undervalued Stocks:</i></b> These are stocks that the analysis suggests are trading below their intrinsic value. Buying undervalued stocks has the potential for higher returns if the market price eventually catches up to the true worth of the company.</br></br><b><i>Overvalued Stocks:</i></b> Conversely, analysis might reveal stocks that are priced higher than their intrinsic value. Investors might choose to avoid these stocks or even short-sell them (expecting that the price will go down).</p></div>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        
if selected == "Technical Analysis":    
        st.markdown("<h2 class='Heading' >Technical Analysis</h2>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        st.markdown("<div class='ans'><div class='imgContainer'><img src='https://www.marketbeat.com/logos/articles/med_20230712104204_how-to-learn-technical-analysis-in-4-steps.jpg' class='img' ><img src='https://i.ibb.co/0C9Pd8f/Screenshot-2024-04-05-223343.png' class='img' ><img src='https://i.ibb.co/fpPC1fh/technical-analysis-mc-slide1.png' class='img' ><img src='https://i.ibb.co/8MRN4pX/Triggers-on-Chart-Patterns.png' class='img' > <img src='https://www.tradingsim.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Imported_Blog_Media/Continuation-Chart-Patterns.png?width=704&name=Continuation-Chart-Patterns.png' class='img' > </div><p class='Para'><b><i>Technical analysis</b></i> is a distinct approach to investment compared to fundamental analysis. Instead of focusing on a company's underlying value, technical analysis examines historical price and trading data to identify patterns and trends that might signal future price movements.</br></br>Here's a breakdown of the core concepts in technical analysis: </br></br> <b><i>Charts:</i></b> Technical analysts rely heavily on charts that visually represent a security's price movements over time. These charts can be line graphs, bar charts, or specialized candlestick charts that depict more information like opening and closing prices. </br></br><b><i>Technical Indicators:</i></b> Various mathematical formulas are applied to price and volume data to generate technical indicators. These indicators are tools that help analysts identify trends, potential buying and selling zones, and signal strength. Some common examples include moving averages, relative strength index (RSI), and Bollinger BandsÂ®. </br></br><b><i>Support and Resistance Levels:</i></b> These are key price levels that a security tends to bounce off or break through. Support levels are where the price has historically stopped falling, while resistance levels are where the price has stopped rising. Technical analysts use these levels to identify potential entry and exit points. </br></br><b><i>Volume:</i></b> Volume refers to the number of shares traded in a security over a given period. Technical analysts believe that volume can provide valuable insights into the strength of a price movement. For example, a price increase accompanied by high volume might indicate strong buying interest and vice versa. </br></br><b><i>Price Patterns:</i></b> Technical analysts also study recurring patterns formed by price movements on charts. These patterns are believed to represent psychological tendencies of investors and might indicate potential future price direction. However, the validity of these patterns is debated.</br></br>The Goal of Technical Analysis:</br></br><b><i>Identify Trading Opportunities:</i></b> Technical analysis helps traders spot potential entry and exit points for buying and selling securities based on perceived signals from the price movements.</br></br><b><i>Gauge Market Sentiment:</i></b> Technical indicators can reflect the overall sentiment of the market towards a particular security, indicating bullishness (buying pressure) or bearishness (selling pressure).</br></br><b><i>Manage Risk:</i></b> Some technical indicators can be used to assess potential risk involved in a trade, helping investors make informed decisions about position sizing and stop-loss orders.</p></div>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        
if selected == "Candlestick Chart":
        st.markdown("<h2 class='Heading' >Candlestick Chart</h2>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        st.markdown("<div class='ans'><div class='imgContainer'><img src='https://www.incrediblecharts.com/images/candlesticks/candlestick-colors.svg' class='img' ><img src='https://www.gomarkets.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Rom-Chart-2.png' class='img'><img src='https://media.istockphoto.com/id/867941110/vector/stock-exchange.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=DKvdbZg3XR0JQsN59dF-kSoU9Gz62t6Io-IsJP88pVw=' class='img'></div><p class='Para'>A <b><i>candlestick chart </i></b>is a visual tool used in financial markets to depict price movements of a security (stock, currency, commodity) over a specific period. It condenses four important pieces of price information into a single bar:</br></br><b><i>Open:</i></b> The price at which the security started trading during that period (typically a day).</br><b><i>Close:</i></b> The price at which the security finished trading during that period.</br><b><i>High:</i></b> The highest price the security reached during that period.</br><b><i>Low:</i></b> The lowest price the security reached during that period.</br></br>The body of the candlestick represents the difference between the opening and closing prices.  If the closing price was higher than the opening price (upward movement), the body is filled in (often colored green or white). Conversely, if the closing price was lower (downward movement), the body is hollow (often colored red or black). </br></br><b><i>Upper Wick:</i></b> This line extends upwards from the top of the body. It represents the highest price the security reached during that period compared to the closing price.</br><b><i>Lower Wick:</i></b> This line extends downwards from the bottom of the body. It represents the lowest price the security reached during that period compared to the opening price.</p></div>", unsafe_allow_html=True)

if selected == "Indicators":  
        st.markdown("<h2 class='Heading' >Indicators</h2>", unsafe_allow_html=True)
        st.markdown("<div class='ans'><div class='imgContainer'><img src='https://dailypriceaction.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/technical-indicators.png' class='img' ><img src='https://i.ibb.co/hK5FTCq/Screenshot-2024-04-05-230918.png' class='img' > <img src='https://i.ibb.co/GJvvYnG/Screenshot-2024-04-05-231254.png' class='img' ></div><p class='Para'><b><i>Technical indicators</i></b> are mathematical calculations applied to a security's price and volume data. These calculations are designed to help investors identify trends, potential buying and selling opportunities, and assess the risk involved in a trade.</br></br><b><i>Trend Following Indicators:</i></b>These indicators aim to capture the overall direction (uptrend, downtrend, or sideways movement) of a security's price. Some common examples include-</br><b><i>Moving Averages:</i></b> A calculated average price over a specific period (e.g., 50-day moving average). The price moving above its moving average can indicate an uptrend, while the reverse suggests a downtrend.</br><b><i>Exponential Moving Average:</i></b> Similar to moving averages, but gives more weight to recent prices, making it more responsive to recent price changes.</br></br><b><i>Momentum Indicators:</i></b>These indicators focus on the speed and magnitude of price movements, helping gauge market sentiment and potential trend strength. Some popular examples include-</br><b><i>Relative Strength Index (RSI):</i></b> Measures the speed and magnitude of recent price changes to identify overbought or oversold conditions. An RSI above 70 might suggest an overbought security, while an RSI below 30 might indicate an oversold security.</br><b><i>Bollinger BandsÂ®:</i></b> These are volatility bands plotted around a moving average. The width of the bands expands and contracts based on volatility. Narrow bands might suggest low volatility and a potential breakout, while wide bands indicate high volatility.</p></div>", unsafe_allow_html=True)

        


